1
00:00:40,665 --> 00:00:45,169
BOY: <i>"In the decade of the 19303,
even the great city of Metropolis...</i>

2
00:00:45,336 --> 00:00:49,131
<i>...was not spared the ravages
of the worldwide depression.</i>

3
00:00:49,298 --> 00:00:53,803
<i>In the times of fear and confusion,
the job of informing the public...</i>

4
00:00:53,970 --> 00:00:56,847
<i>...was the responsibility
of the</i> Daily <i>Planet...</i>

5
00:00:57,014 --> 00:01:02,395
<i>...a great metropolitan newspaper,
whose reputation for clarity and truth...</i>

6
00:01:02,562 --> 00:01:07,525
<i>...had become a symbol of hope
for the city of Metropolis."</i>

7
00:06:40,983 --> 00:06:44,153
MAN:
This is no fantasy...

8
00:06:44,320 --> 00:06:47,990
...no careless product
of wild imagination.

9
00:06:48,157 --> 00:06:50,826
No, my good friends...

10
00:06:52,161 --> 00:06:58,083
These indictments
I have brought you today...

11
00:06:58,500 --> 00:07:03,505
...the specific charges listed herein
against the individuals...

12
00:07:03,672 --> 00:07:08,302
...their acts of treason,
their ultimate aim of sedition...

13
00:07:10,679 --> 00:07:16,936
...these are matters of undeniable fact.

14
00:07:19,396 --> 00:07:24,193
I ask you now to pronounce judgment...

15
00:07:24,360 --> 00:07:27,196
...on those accused.

16
00:07:33,535 --> 00:07:35,371
On this...

17
00:07:35,537 --> 00:07:39,875
This mindless aberration,
whose only means of expression...

18
00:07:40,042 --> 00:07:42,252
...are wanton violence and destruction.

19
00:07:45,631 --> 00:07:46,882
On the woman, Ursa...

20
00:07:47,049 --> 00:07:50,594
...whose perversions
and unreasoning hatred of all mankind...

21
00:07:50,761 --> 00:07:54,640
...have threatened even the children
of the planet Krypton.

22
00:08:03,107 --> 00:08:05,651
Finally, General Zod.

23
00:08:06,735 --> 00:08:09,071
Once trusted by this council...

24
00:08:09,238 --> 00:08:12,825
...charged with maintaining the defense
of the planet Krypton itself.

25
00:08:12,992 --> 00:08:15,244
Chief architect
of this intended revolution...

26
00:08:15,411 --> 00:08:21,250
...and author of this insidious plot
to establish a new order amongst us...

27
00:08:21,917 --> 00:08:24,962
...with himself as absolute ruler.

28
00:08:27,423 --> 00:08:29,758
You have heard the evidence.

29
00:08:30,592 --> 00:08:33,095
The decision of the council
will now be heard.

30
00:08:33,262 --> 00:08:34,596
<i>Guilty.</i>

31
00:08:35,514 --> 00:08:37,683
COUNCILMAN:
<i>Guilty.</i>

32
00:08:38,642 --> 00:08:39,935
<i>Guilty.</i>

33
00:08:43,105 --> 00:08:45,190
The vote must be unanimous, Jor-El.

34
00:08:46,150 --> 00:08:48,652
It has therefore
now become your decision.

35
00:08:48,819 --> 00:08:51,155
You alone
will condemn us if you wish...

36
00:08:51,321 --> 00:08:54,283
...and you alone
will be held responsible by me.

37
00:09:03,167 --> 00:09:04,460
Join us.

38
00:09:05,919 --> 00:09:09,631
You have been known to disagree
with the council before.

39
00:09:09,798 --> 00:09:12,468
Yours could become an important voice
in the new order...

40
00:09:12,634 --> 00:09:14,511
...second only to my own.

41
00:09:15,137 --> 00:09:18,223
I offer you a chance
for greatness, Jor-El!

42
00:09:18,432 --> 00:09:21,518
Take it! Join us!

43
00:09:22,436 --> 00:09:24,813
You will bow down before me, Jor-El.

44
00:09:24,980 --> 00:09:26,231
I swear it.

45
00:09:26,440 --> 00:09:31,320
No matter that it takes an eternity,
you will bow down before me!

46
00:09:31,487 --> 00:09:32,821
Both you...

47
00:09:32,988 --> 00:09:33,989
...and then one day...

48
00:09:34,156 --> 00:09:36,492
...your heirs!

49
00:10:53,944 --> 00:10:55,821
No!

50
00:10:56,029 --> 00:10:59,449
- Let us out of here!
- Help me!

51
00:11:05,122 --> 00:11:07,583
URSA: Forgive me!
ZOD: I shall return!

52
00:11:07,749 --> 00:11:09,084
Forgive me!

53
00:11:09,251 --> 00:11:11,753
I shall return!

54
00:11:14,965 --> 00:11:17,759
You cannot ignore these facts.

55
00:11:18,135 --> 00:11:21,471
It's suicide. No, it's worse.

56
00:11:21,638 --> 00:11:22,848
It's genocide.

57
00:11:23,056 --> 00:11:24,933
Be warned, Jor-El.

58
00:11:25,100 --> 00:11:29,479
The council has already evaluated
this outlandish theory of yours.

59
00:11:30,647 --> 00:11:34,943
My friends, you know me to be
neither rash nor impulsive.

60
00:11:35,110 --> 00:11:40,115
I am not given to wild,
unsupported statements.

61
00:11:40,282 --> 00:11:43,785
And I tell you that we must
evacuate this planet immediately.

62
00:11:44,119 --> 00:11:48,290
It isn't that we question your data.
The facts are undeniable.

63
00:11:52,002 --> 00:11:55,464
It's your conclusions
we find unsupportable.

64
00:11:57,799 --> 00:12:02,721
This planet will explode
within 30 days, if not sooner.

65
00:12:02,888 --> 00:12:05,474
I tell you, Krypton
is simply shifting its orbit.

66
00:12:05,807 --> 00:12:09,519
Jor-El, be reasonable.

67
00:12:10,979 --> 00:12:12,856
My friend...

68
00:12:14,399 --> 00:12:16,026
...I have never been otherwise.

69
00:12:16,735 --> 00:12:18,320
This madness is yours.

70
00:12:18,487 --> 00:12:21,240
This discussion is terminated.

71
00:12:21,698 --> 00:12:25,327
The decision of the council is final.

72
00:12:44,012 --> 00:12:50,018
Any attempt by you to create a climate
of fear and panic among the populace...

73
00:12:50,185 --> 00:12:54,231
...must be deemed by us
an act of insurrection.

74
00:12:54,398 --> 00:12:57,526
You would accuse me of insurrection?

75
00:12:57,901 --> 00:13:00,779
Has it now become a crime
to cherish life?

76
00:13:04,074 --> 00:13:08,870
Will you abide by the council's decision?

77
00:13:13,375 --> 00:13:15,961
I will remain silent.

78
00:13:16,545 --> 00:13:22,050
Neither I, nor my wife
will leave Krypton.

79
00:13:50,579 --> 00:13:52,331
[MACHINERY HUMMING]

80
00:13:57,586 --> 00:13:59,463
[BABY CRIES]

81
00:14:14,227 --> 00:14:15,437
Have you finished?

82
00:14:18,774 --> 00:14:20,609
Nearly.

83
00:14:25,322 --> 00:14:27,199
It's the only answer, Lara.

84
00:14:27,366 --> 00:14:32,621
If he remains here with us
he will die as surely as we will.

85
00:14:32,788 --> 00:14:34,122
<i>But why Earth, Jer-El?</i>

86
00:14:34,289 --> 00:14:36,958
They're primitives,
thousands of years behind us.

87
00:14:37,125 --> 00:14:39,795
He will need that advantage to survive.

88
00:14:41,963 --> 00:14:46,635
Their atmosphere will sustain him.

89
00:14:54,768 --> 00:14:56,686
He will defy their gravity.

90
00:14:56,853 --> 00:14:59,314
He will look like one of them.

91
00:14:59,648 --> 00:15:01,817
He won't be one of them.

92
00:15:01,983 --> 00:15:03,693
No.

93
00:15:03,860 --> 00:15:07,489
His dense molecular structure
will make him strong.

94
00:15:08,865 --> 00:15:12,828
He'll be odd. Different.

95
00:15:13,578 --> 00:15:18,083
He'll be fast. Virtually invulnerable.

96
00:15:18,291 --> 00:15:22,003
Isolated, alone.

97
00:15:24,005 --> 00:15:25,048
[EXHALES SHARPLY]

98
00:15:25,215 --> 00:15:27,509
He will not be alone.

99
00:15:33,014 --> 00:15:35,517
He will never be alone.

100
00:16:23,607 --> 00:16:28,278
You will travel far, my little Kal-El.

101
00:16:29,613 --> 00:16:31,948
But we will never leave you...

102
00:16:32,657 --> 00:16:35,744
...even in the face of our deaths.

103
00:16:35,911 --> 00:16:41,917
The richness of our lives,
it will be yours.

104
00:16:42,459 --> 00:16:46,796
All that I have, all that I've learned,
everything I feel...

105
00:16:47,255 --> 00:16:49,799
...all this and more...

106
00:16:51,301 --> 00:16:54,137
...I bequeath you, my son.

107
00:16:56,806 --> 00:17:02,646
You will carry me inside you
all the days of your life.

108
00:17:03,980 --> 00:17:09,778
You will make my strength your own,
see my life through your eyes...

109
00:17:09,945 --> 00:17:12,989
...as your life
will be seen through mine.

110
00:17:15,534 --> 00:17:19,704
The son becomes the father,
and the father the son.

111
00:17:24,292 --> 00:17:26,336
This is all I...

112
00:17:28,630 --> 00:17:30,799
All I can send you...

113
00:17:31,800 --> 00:17:33,176
...Kal-El.

114
00:17:47,983 --> 00:17:50,068
[HIGH-PITCHED WHINE]

115
00:17:56,950 --> 00:17:58,827
[EXPLODING OUTSIDE]

116
00:19:04,559 --> 00:19:05,935
[CRYSTALS SHATTERING]

117
00:19:09,272 --> 00:19:11,066
[BEEPING]

118
00:19:15,070 --> 00:19:17,238
[BEEPING FASTER]

119
00:19:53,650 --> 00:19:55,610
[SCREAMING]

120
00:20:07,622 --> 00:20:10,166
[HIGH-PITCHED WHINE]

121
00:21:45,094 --> 00:21:47,222
JOR-EL [OVER CRYSTAL]:
<i>- -Which Einstein called...</i>

122
00:21:47,388 --> 00:21:48,556
<i>...his theory of relativity.</i>

123
00:21:48,723 --> 00:21:53,770
<i>Embedded in the crystals before you is
the total accumulation of all literature...</i>

124
00:21:53,937 --> 00:21:56,773
<i>...and scientific fact
from dozens of other worlds...</i>

125
00:21:56,940 --> 00:22:00,235
<i>...spanning the 28 known galaxies.</i>

126
00:22:19,963 --> 00:22:24,843
<i>Early Chinese writings
point out the complex relationships.</i>...

127
00:22:27,220 --> 00:22:30,598
<i>By carrying this complex equation
to its ultimate power, my son...</i>

128
00:22:34,936 --> 00:22:37,272
<i>Chief among these powers
will be your sight...</i>

129
00:22:37,438 --> 00:22:39,315
<i>...your strength, your hearing...</i>

130
00:22:39,482 --> 00:22:44,320
<i>...your ability to propel yourself
at almost limitless speed.</i>

131
00:22:44,487 --> 00:22:49,492
<i>The early history of our universe was
a bloody mosaic of interplanetary war.</i>

132
00:22:49,659 --> 00:22:52,620
<i>Each of the six galaxies
which you will pass through...</i>

133
00:22:52,787 --> 00:22:55,623
<i>...contain their own individual law,
space and time.</i>

134
00:22:55,790 --> 00:22:59,961
<i>It is forbidden for you
to interfere with human history.</i>

135
00:23:11,389 --> 00:23:13,391
[SIZZLING]

136
00:23:31,659 --> 00:23:32,827
[CRASHES]
[SCREAMS]

137
00:23:33,036 --> 00:23:34,787
What was that?

138
00:23:36,873 --> 00:23:38,833
[TIRE POPS]

139
00:23:58,186 --> 00:24:00,104
Now, wouldn't that beat all get-out?

140
00:24:00,313 --> 00:24:01,940
Will you--? You...

141
00:24:10,823 --> 00:24:11,908
Pa...

142
00:24:12,867 --> 00:24:14,744
Oh, my.

143
00:24:39,060 --> 00:24:40,395
[METAL CLANGS]

144
00:24:41,854 --> 00:24:43,898
[GRUNTING]

145
00:24:47,360 --> 00:24:49,404
All these years,
as happy as we've been...

146
00:24:49,570 --> 00:24:51,406
...how I've prayed the good Lord...

147
00:24:51,572 --> 00:24:54,117
...see fit to give us a child.

148
00:24:55,618 --> 00:24:58,121
Honey, will you hand me
that rag up there?

149
00:24:58,287 --> 00:24:59,789
You take things easy, Jonathan.

150
00:24:59,956 --> 00:25:02,500
Remember what Doc Frye said
about that heart of yours.

151
00:25:08,464 --> 00:25:12,427
Now, the first thing we've got
to do when we get home is find out...

152
00:25:12,593 --> 00:25:14,595
...who that boy's proper family is.

153
00:25:15,638 --> 00:25:18,766
He hasn't got any.
Not around here, anyway.

154
00:25:22,520 --> 00:25:25,189
Martha, are you thinking
what I think you're thinking?

155
00:25:26,274 --> 00:25:30,486
We could say he's the child
of my cousin in North Dakota.

156
00:25:30,653 --> 00:25:31,988
And just now orphaned.

157
00:25:33,781 --> 00:25:36,951
- Oh, Martha.
- Jonathan, he's only a baby.

158
00:25:37,118 --> 00:25:40,913
Martha...
Now, you saw how we found him.

159
00:25:44,000 --> 00:25:47,170
Martha Clark Kent, are you
listening to what I'm saying?

160
00:25:48,004 --> 00:25:49,922
Jonathan!

161
00:26:19,077 --> 00:26:20,161
[WHISTLE BLOWS]

162
00:26:20,328 --> 00:26:22,080
Come on, gang.

163
00:26:23,206 --> 00:26:24,832
BOY 1:
Come on.

164
00:26:24,999 --> 00:26:27,710
BOY 2: Great game, huh?
BOY 3: Next week we'll knock them out.

165
00:26:28,377 --> 00:26:30,046
GIRL 1:
All right.

166
00:26:31,214 --> 00:26:32,673
Come on, gang, hustle. Let's go.

167
00:26:32,840 --> 00:26:34,383
Stack your helmets neatly.

168
00:26:34,550 --> 00:26:37,553
Remember about those uniforms.
Cleaned and washed by tomorrow...

169
00:26:37,720 --> 00:26:39,764
...and looking like a football team.

170
00:26:39,972 --> 00:26:41,891
Clark, have the clothes
washed and ready...

171
00:26:42,058 --> 00:26:43,684
- ...for tomorrow's game.
- Yes, sir.

172
00:26:43,851 --> 00:26:45,228
Got to beat Mount Vernon High!

173
00:26:45,394 --> 00:26:48,356
BOY 4: Can you give me a lift?
COACH: Home early!

174
00:26:53,528 --> 00:26:56,697
Lana? Don't bother with these, huh?

175
00:26:56,864 --> 00:26:59,575
I'll take them in with
the other equipment.

176
00:26:59,742 --> 00:27:02,537
- Thank you, Clark.
- Sure.

177
00:27:03,287 --> 00:27:06,082
Listen, a whole bunch of us
are going up to Mary Ellen's...

178
00:27:06,249 --> 00:27:07,875
...play some records...

179
00:27:08,626 --> 00:27:10,044
Would you like to come?

180
00:27:11,587 --> 00:27:14,715
Sure. Sounds like it'd be a lot of fun.

181
00:27:14,882 --> 00:27:17,552
Kent can't make it.
Still got a lot of work to do.

182
00:27:17,927 --> 00:27:20,763
What are you talking about?
I just finished stacking all the--

183
00:27:20,930 --> 00:27:22,306
- All that?
- Oh.

184
00:27:22,890 --> 00:27:24,767
Oh, Brad.

185
00:27:25,143 --> 00:27:28,896
GIRL 2: Hey, come on, Lana.
BRAD: Come on, Lana.

186
00:27:29,063 --> 00:27:30,731
Come on, let's go.

187
00:27:31,274 --> 00:27:32,942
- He's got to clean up.
- Bye, Clark.

188
00:27:33,109 --> 00:27:35,778
- Yeah. Bye, Lana.
- Clean this up, Clark.

189
00:27:37,071 --> 00:27:38,489
GIRL 3: Let's go.
GIRL 4: Bye, Clark.

190
00:27:38,656 --> 00:27:41,284
BOY 5: We're off to Mary Ellen's.
GIRL 4: See you, Clark.

191
00:27:42,034 --> 00:27:43,452
GIRL 3:
All right.

192
00:27:44,620 --> 00:27:46,247
GIRL 4: Bye, Clark.
BOY 5: Bye, Clark.

193
00:27:46,414 --> 00:27:49,625
GIRL 3: Bye, Clark. See you tomorrow.
Bye-bye.

194
00:28:11,355 --> 00:28:12,940
[TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWS]

195
00:28:48,476 --> 00:28:49,644
Whoo-hoo!

196
00:29:13,125 --> 00:29:14,919
[TEENS CHATTERING]

197
00:29:15,169 --> 00:29:18,339
[BILL HALEY & HIS COMETS' "ROCK
AROUND THE CLOCK" PLAYS ON THE RADIO]

198
00:29:30,768 --> 00:29:32,853
Hey, look. There's Clark.

199
00:29:33,020 --> 00:29:35,356
BOY:
How come he's here?

200
00:29:35,523 --> 00:29:37,525
Clark.

201
00:29:37,692 --> 00:29:39,360
How'd you get here so fast?

202
00:29:40,403 --> 00:29:43,030
- I ran.
BRAD: Ran, huh?

203
00:29:43,197 --> 00:29:46,284
Told you he's an oddball.
Let's get out of here.

204
00:29:53,249 --> 00:29:55,793
Been showing off a bit,
haven't you, son?

205
00:30:03,676 --> 00:30:05,052
Uh...

206
00:30:08,180 --> 00:30:10,391
I didn't mean to show off, Pa.

207
00:30:13,811 --> 00:30:17,273
It's just that, guys like that Brad,
I just want to tear them apart.

208
00:30:17,440 --> 00:30:19,317
Yeah. I know.

209
00:30:19,483 --> 00:30:21,610
- Yeah, I know I shouldn't.
- Yeah, I know...

210
00:30:21,777 --> 00:30:23,779
...you can do all these amazing things...

211
00:30:23,946 --> 00:30:26,657
...and sometimes you think
that you will just go bust...

212
00:30:26,824 --> 00:30:28,617
...unless you can tell people about it.

213
00:30:28,784 --> 00:30:31,620
Yeah. I mean, every time
I get the football...

214
00:30:31,787 --> 00:30:34,665
- ...I can make a touchdown. Every time.
- That's for sure.

215
00:30:34,832 --> 00:30:37,335
I mean, is it showing off
if somebody's doing...

216
00:30:37,501 --> 00:30:41,130
...the things he's capable of doing?
Is a bird showing off when it flies?

217
00:30:41,297 --> 00:30:44,467
No. No, now you listen to me.

218
00:30:44,633 --> 00:30:46,802
When you first came to us,
we thought people...

219
00:30:46,969 --> 00:30:49,638
...would come take you away
because when they found out...

220
00:30:49,805 --> 00:30:53,476
...you know, the things you could do,
and that worried us a lot.

221
00:30:53,642 --> 00:30:56,520
Then a man gets older,
and he thinks very differently...

222
00:30:56,729 --> 00:30:59,440
...and things get very clear.

223
00:30:59,607 --> 00:31:01,442
And there's one thing I do know, son...

224
00:31:01,609 --> 00:31:05,029
...and that is you are here for a reason.

225
00:31:05,237 --> 00:31:07,615
I don't know whose reason,
but whatever the reason...

226
00:31:07,782 --> 00:31:09,784
...maybe it's because...

227
00:31:13,496 --> 00:31:15,289
I don't know, it's...

228
00:31:16,999 --> 00:31:18,834
But I do know one thing:

229
00:31:19,001 --> 00:31:21,670
It's not to score touchdowns.

230
00:31:21,837 --> 00:31:23,255
Huh?

231
00:31:24,006 --> 00:31:25,508
Thanks, Dad.

232
00:31:26,842 --> 00:31:28,803
I'll race you to it. Dad.

233
00:31:28,969 --> 00:31:30,971
- You will, huh?
- Come on. Come on, Pop, run.

234
00:31:31,138 --> 00:31:33,224
Come on. Move. Move.
Yeah, 90, go, 90. Come on, run.

235
00:31:33,391 --> 00:31:34,475
[DOG BARKING]

236
00:31:34,642 --> 00:31:37,812
Hey, Baron! Hey, Baron. Hey, boy.

237
00:31:39,063 --> 00:31:40,648
[PANTING]

238
00:31:44,693 --> 00:31:46,654
Oh, no.

239
00:32:02,878 --> 00:32:04,547
Jonathan.

240
00:32:06,549 --> 00:32:08,717
Jonathan!

241
00:32:14,348 --> 00:32:15,850
Dad.

242
00:32:18,018 --> 00:32:19,353
No!

243
00:32:22,731 --> 00:32:24,692
Jonathan!

244
00:32:26,735 --> 00:32:28,571
No!

245
00:33:06,442 --> 00:33:08,652
All those things I can do...

246
00:33:10,154 --> 00:33:12,239
All those powers...

247
00:33:14,909 --> 00:33:17,244
And I couldn't even save him.

248
00:34:05,626 --> 00:34:07,336
[STATIC ON RADIO]

249
00:34:18,639 --> 00:34:19,807
[STATIC STOPS]

250
00:36:02,117 --> 00:36:05,412
[ROOSTER CROWING]

251
00:36:12,586 --> 00:36:14,630
[BARON BARKING]

252
00:37:04,513 --> 00:37:06,348
I have to leave.

253
00:37:12,187 --> 00:37:14,648
I knew this time would come.

254
00:37:15,482 --> 00:37:17,151
We both knew it...

255
00:37:17,317 --> 00:37:19,486
...from the day we found you.

256
00:37:30,164 --> 00:37:32,875
I talked to Ben Hubbard yesterday...

257
00:37:33,167 --> 00:37:39,381
...and he said that he'd be happy
to help out from now on.

258
00:37:47,556 --> 00:37:49,183
Mother...

259
00:37:50,184 --> 00:37:52,186
I know, son.

260
00:37:53,854 --> 00:37:55,564
I know.

261
00:37:59,359 --> 00:38:02,780
Do you know where you're headed?

262
00:38:06,658 --> 00:38:08,076
North.

263
00:38:13,415 --> 00:38:15,417
Remember us, son.

264
00:38:17,252 --> 00:38:19,087
Always remember us.

265
00:40:24,004 --> 00:40:26,048
[HIGH-PITCHED WHINE]

266
00:43:17,594 --> 00:43:19,679
[CRYSTAL WHINES]

267
00:43:55,590 --> 00:43:57,717
<i>My son...</i>

268
00:44:04,099 --> 00:44:06,560
<i>...you do not remember me.</i>

269
00:44:07,519 --> 00:44:09,229
<i>I am Jor-El.</i>

270
00:44:10,272 --> 00:44:11,731
<i>I'm your father.</i>

271
00:44:14,234 --> 00:44:17,279
<i>By now, you will have reached
your 18th year...</i>

272
00:44:17,445 --> 00:44:20,115
<i>...as it is measured on Earth.</i>

273
00:44:20,282 --> 00:44:23,743
<i>By that reckoning,
I will have been dead...</i>

274
00:44:23,910 --> 00:44:27,164
<i>...for many thousands of your years.</i>

275
00:44:28,415 --> 00:44:30,792
<i>The knowledge...</i>

276
00:44:30,959 --> 00:44:34,588
<i>...that I have,
matters physical and historic...</i>

277
00:44:34,754 --> 00:44:38,925
<i>...I've given you fully on your voyage
to your new home.</i>

278
00:44:39,092 --> 00:44:44,556
<i>These are important matters, to be sure,
but still matters of mere fact.</i>

279
00:44:46,057 --> 00:44:48,852
<i>There are questions to be asked.</i>

280
00:44:49,060 --> 00:44:52,772
<i>And it is time for you to do so.</i>

281
00:44:54,608 --> 00:44:56,443
<i>Here in this...</i>

282
00:44:57,277 --> 00:45:00,697
<i>This Fortress of Solitude...</i>

283
00:45:01,489 --> 00:45:04,159
<i>...we shall try to find
the answers together.</i>

284
00:45:05,952 --> 00:45:08,538
<i>So, my son...</i>

285
00:45:08,705 --> 00:45:10,290
<i>...speak.</i>

286
00:45:11,333 --> 00:45:13,084
Who am I?

287
00:45:13,501 --> 00:45:15,670
<i>Your name is Kai-El.</i>

288
00:45:16,463 --> 00:45:20,175
<i>You are the only survivor
of the planet Krypton.</i>

289
00:45:20,592 --> 00:45:23,053
<i>Even though you've been
raised as a human being...</i>

290
00:45:23,220 --> 00:45:25,138
<i>...you are not one of them.</i>

291
00:45:25,805 --> 00:45:27,974
<i>You have great powers...</i>

292
00:45:28,141 --> 00:45:32,229
<i>...only some of which
you have as yet discovered.</i>

293
00:45:34,689 --> 00:45:36,233
<i>Come with me now, my son...</i>

294
00:45:36,399 --> 00:45:39,236
...as <i>we break through the bonds
of your earthly confinement.</i>

295
00:45:39,402 --> 00:45:42,906
<i>Traveling through time and space
in the six known dimensions.</i>

296
00:45:43,114 --> 00:45:46,493
<i>Your powers will far exceed
those of mortal men.</i>

297
00:45:46,660 --> 00:45:49,746
<i>It is forbidden for you to interfere
with human history.</i>

298
00:45:49,913 --> 00:45:53,667
<i>Rather, let your leadership
stir others to.</i>

299
00:45:54,918 --> 00:45:59,839
<i>In this next year, we shall
examine the human heart.</i>

300
00:46:00,006 --> 00:46:02,717
<i>It is more fragile than your own.</i>

301
00:46:02,884 --> 00:46:04,094
<i>For the past two years--</i>

302
00:46:04,261 --> 00:46:08,765
<i>As we pass through the flaming turmoil
which is the edge of your own galaxy...</i>

303
00:46:08,932 --> 00:46:11,351
<i>...we'll enter the realm
of the red Krypton sun...</i>

304
00:46:11,518 --> 00:46:14,104
<i>...source of your strength
and nourishment...</i>

305
00:46:14,271 --> 00:46:17,023
<i>...cause of our eventual destruction.</i>

306
00:46:18,024 --> 00:46:21,027
<i>The planet Krypton, my son.</i>

307
00:46:21,194 --> 00:46:24,531
<i>Your home, as it was.</i>

308
00:46:25,657 --> 00:46:29,744
<i>This year, we shall examine
the various concepts of immortality...</i>

309
00:46:29,911 --> 00:46:32,706
<i>...and their basis in actual fact.</i>

310
00:46:32,956 --> 00:46:37,544
<i>The total accumulation of all knowledge,
spanning the 28 known galaxies...</i>

311
00:46:37,711 --> 00:46:41,089
<i>...is embedded in the crystals
which I have sent along with you.</i>

312
00:46:41,256 --> 00:46:43,300
<i>Study them well, my son...</i>

313
00:46:43,466 --> 00:46:46,303
<i>...and learn from them.
We've reasoned out logical judgments.</i>

314
00:46:46,469 --> 00:46:49,889
<i>By the time you return
to the confines of your galaxy...</i>

315
00:46:50,056 --> 00:46:52,767
<i>...twelve of your years
will have passed.</i>

316
00:46:52,934 --> 00:46:57,897
<i>For this reason, among others,
I have chosen Earth for you.</i>

317
00:46:58,064 --> 00:47:01,401
<i>It is now time for you
to rejoin your new world...</i>

318
00:47:01,568 --> 00:47:05,280
<i>...and to serve its collective humanity.</i>

319
00:47:05,447 --> 00:47:07,907
<i>Live as one of them, Kai-El...</i>

320
00:47:08,074 --> 00:47:11,619
<i>...to discover where your strength
and your power are needed.</i>

321
00:47:11,786 --> 00:47:17,500
<i>Always hold in your heart
the pride of your special heritage.</i>

322
00:47:17,709 --> 00:47:21,004
<i>They can be a great people, Kai-El.
They wish to be.</i>

323
00:47:21,588 --> 00:47:24,716
<i>They only lack the light
to show the way.</i>

324
00:47:25,759 --> 00:47:29,971
<i>For this reason above all,
their capacity for good...</i>

325
00:47:30,513 --> 00:47:32,724
<i>...I have sent them you...</i>

326
00:47:34,225 --> 00:47:36,144
<i>...my only son.</i>

327
00:48:01,836 --> 00:48:03,338
[WHISTLE BLOWING]

328
00:48:03,505 --> 00:48:05,298
[HORNS HONKING]

329
00:48:11,638 --> 00:48:14,891
CAB DRIVER:
Okay, this is it, Mac, the <i>Daily Planet.</i>

330
00:48:15,058 --> 00:48:17,143
Fresh fruit. Hey, lady,
how about a tomato?

331
00:48:17,310 --> 00:48:19,187
Fresh fruit.
Hey, baby, how's it going?

332
00:48:19,354 --> 00:48:23,650
Hey, fresh fruit and vegetables.
They're so fresh...

333
00:48:24,401 --> 00:48:26,986
Fresh fruit and vegetables.
Get them while they're hot.

334
00:48:27,153 --> 00:48:29,656
Look at these tomatoes.
Aren't they beautiful?

335
00:48:29,823 --> 00:48:31,032
[PEOPLE CHATTERING]

336
00:48:31,282 --> 00:48:32,659
[TYPEWRITER KEYS CLACKING]

337
00:48:32,867 --> 00:48:35,036
[PHONE RINGING]

338
00:48:41,835 --> 00:48:45,088
He did a great job.
You see his article this morning?

339
00:48:53,847 --> 00:48:55,557
JIMMY:
Smile.

340
00:48:57,183 --> 00:49:00,603
- How many T's in "bloodletting"?
- Two.

341
00:49:06,609 --> 00:49:09,028
- What are you writing, Miss Lane?
- An ode to spring.

342
00:49:09,195 --> 00:49:11,197
- How do you spell "massacre"?
- Uh...

343
00:49:11,364 --> 00:49:15,702
- M-A-S-S-A-C-R-E.
- A... C...

344
00:49:15,869 --> 00:49:17,579
...R-E. Thank you.

345
00:49:17,745 --> 00:49:19,956
Golly, how come you get
all the great stories?

346
00:49:20,123 --> 00:49:22,375
A good reporter doesn't
get great stories, Jimmy.

347
00:49:22,542 --> 00:49:24,377
- A good reporter makes them great.
- Makes them great.

348
00:49:24,544 --> 00:49:26,212
Here's that story
on the East Side murder.

349
00:49:26,379 --> 00:49:29,466
I see it as a banner headline,
front page, maybe my picture--

350
00:49:29,632 --> 00:49:32,760
There's only one P in "rapist."
Lois Lane, say hello to Clark Kent.

351
00:49:32,927 --> 00:49:35,221
- Told you one P.
- Hello, Miss Lane. How are--?

352
00:49:35,388 --> 00:49:37,724
LOIS: Remember my expose
on the sex and drug orgies...

353
00:49:37,891 --> 00:49:39,476
...in the senior citizens' home?

354
00:49:39,642 --> 00:49:41,644
How you doing?
Jimmy Olsen, photographer.

355
00:49:41,853 --> 00:49:44,731
- Oh, hi. Clark Kent. Nice to meet you.
- Yeah.

356
00:49:44,898 --> 00:49:47,942
It's got everything. It's got sex,
violence, the ethnic angle--

357
00:49:48,109 --> 00:49:50,570
So does a lady wrestler
with a foreign accent.

358
00:49:50,737 --> 00:49:52,989
- Kent, can you open this?
- Oh, sure, Mr. White.

359
00:49:53,156 --> 00:49:54,824
This could be a series of articles:

360
00:49:54,991 --> 00:49:58,077
"Making Sense of Senseless Killings,"
by Lois Lane.

361
00:49:58,244 --> 00:50:00,747
We get psychologists, sociologists--

362
00:50:00,914 --> 00:50:04,501
Lois, you're pushing a bunch
of rinky-dink tabloid garbage.

363
00:50:04,667 --> 00:50:07,295
- The <i>Daily Planet</i> has a tradition--
- Oh, I'm sorry.

364
00:50:08,004 --> 00:50:11,090
Gosh, I'm sorry.
I didn't mean to shake it up like that.

365
00:50:11,257 --> 00:50:13,176
CLARK:
Ch, of course not, Lois.

366
00:50:13,384 --> 00:50:16,930
Why would anyone want to make
a total stranger look like a fool?

367
00:50:19,140 --> 00:50:21,601
- I'll take that.
- Oh, thank-I'm sorry, Mr. White.

368
00:50:21,768 --> 00:50:25,438
Olsen, why am I paying you when
I should have you arrested for loitering?

369
00:50:25,605 --> 00:50:27,190
- Go get Mr... A towel.
- Kent.

370
00:50:27,398 --> 00:50:28,816
- Move, kid, move.
- Right, chief.

371
00:50:28,983 --> 00:50:30,860
- Make mine black, no sugar.
- Right, chief.

372
00:50:31,027 --> 00:50:33,446
- And don't call me sugar.
- "Blood is in Metropolis...

373
00:50:33,613 --> 00:50:35,698
- Right, sugar.
- ...while the crocuses bloom.“

374
00:50:35,907 --> 00:50:38,993
Chief wants coffee, no sugar.
I'll take tea with lemon.

375
00:50:39,202 --> 00:50:42,830
Lois, why don't you take Kent
out to meet everybody, huh?

376
00:50:42,997 --> 00:50:46,209
Just introduce him around.
He's starting with the paper today.

377
00:50:46,417 --> 00:50:47,794
I'm giving him the city beat.

378
00:50:48,545 --> 00:50:51,798
Chief, that's my beat.

379
00:50:51,965 --> 00:50:56,302
Lois, Clark Kent may seem like just
a mild-mannered reporter, but listen...

380
00:50:56,469 --> 00:50:59,847
...not only does he know how to treat
his editor in chief with respect...

381
00:51:00,014 --> 00:51:02,559
...not only does he have a snappy,
punchy prose style...

382
00:51:02,725 --> 00:51:06,646
...but he is, in my 40 years in this
business, the fastest typist I've seen.

383
00:51:06,813 --> 00:51:08,398
- That's great.
- Excuse me. I'm sorry.

384
00:51:08,565 --> 00:51:10,858
Here, you forgot my article.

385
00:51:12,944 --> 00:51:15,071
Oh, excuse me, Mr. White?

386
00:51:15,238 --> 00:51:18,491
I was wondering if perhaps
you could arrange for half my salary...

387
00:51:18,658 --> 00:51:21,578
...to be sent to this address
on a weekly basis.

388
00:51:21,744 --> 00:51:23,329
- Your bookie, right?
- My what?

389
00:51:23,496 --> 00:51:27,584
Don't tell me, he sends a check every
week to his sweet, gray-haired mother.

390
00:51:27,750 --> 00:51:29,752
Actually, she's silver-haired.

391
00:51:31,588 --> 00:51:33,673
I'll see what I can do.

392
00:51:33,840 --> 00:51:36,384
Thank you very much, Mr. White.

393
00:51:36,759 --> 00:51:38,219
Excuse me.

394
00:51:40,179 --> 00:51:41,764
Well...

395
00:51:42,849 --> 00:51:44,350
Any more at home like you?

396
00:51:44,517 --> 00:51:46,686
Not really, no.

397
00:51:49,188 --> 00:51:51,190
I didn't think so.

398
00:51:52,275 --> 00:51:55,778
- Well, get yourself a desk over here.
- Over here?

399
00:51:55,987 --> 00:51:58,906
Yeah, right here.
There are some papers in a pile--

400
00:51:59,365 --> 00:52:02,285
Sorry. Excuse me.

401
00:52:10,752 --> 00:52:12,545
WOMAN: Yeah. It's fantastic.
LOIS: So you-?

402
00:52:12,712 --> 00:52:15,214
- I met this really great guy.
- Hey, fabulous.

403
00:52:15,381 --> 00:52:17,383
Yeah, fabulous.
I met him at this dude ranch.

404
00:52:17,550 --> 00:52:20,470
- Did--? I used to ride.
- Yeah, I haven't been since I was 7.

405
00:52:20,637 --> 00:52:23,723
- Oh, I gotta mail these letters.
- Okay, bye. Good luck tonight.

406
00:52:23,890 --> 00:52:25,391
- Oh, hi, Clark.
- Hi, Lois.

407
00:52:25,558 --> 00:52:27,393
How did you like your first day?

408
00:52:27,560 --> 00:52:31,064
Well, frankly, the hours
were sort of longer than I expected...

409
00:52:31,230 --> 00:52:34,734
...but on the whole, I mean, meeting you
and Jimmy Olsen and Mr. White...

410
00:52:34,901 --> 00:52:36,486
...gosh, I'd say it's been swell.

411
00:52:36,653 --> 00:52:39,238
- Swell?
- Yeah.

412
00:52:40,114 --> 00:52:44,744
You know, Clark, there are
very few people left in the world...

413
00:52:44,911 --> 00:52:47,080
...who feel comfortable
saying that word.

414
00:52:47,246 --> 00:52:48,581
- What word?
- "Swell."

415
00:52:48,748 --> 00:52:51,292
Really? I always thought
it was kind of natural.

416
00:52:51,918 --> 00:52:53,086
Ooh!

417
00:52:53,336 --> 00:52:55,630
- I'm sorry.
- Clark.

418
00:52:55,797 --> 00:52:57,423
MAN:
It's all right.

419
00:52:58,591 --> 00:52:59,926
- Sorry, Lois.
- Oh, hi, Rex.

420
00:53:00,093 --> 00:53:01,761
- Oh, Lois.
- See anything good today?

421
00:53:01,928 --> 00:53:03,471
- Not until you came along.
- Lois?

422
00:53:03,638 --> 00:53:05,348
- Oh, Rex, this is-
- Clark Kent.

423
00:53:05,556 --> 00:53:07,975
- Yeah, hi, see you around.
- Bye.

424
00:53:09,686 --> 00:53:12,647
- Lois?
- Hey, where you going?

425
00:53:12,814 --> 00:53:15,483
- Can I help you with your coat?
- Oh, yeah. Thanks.

426
00:53:16,067 --> 00:53:18,444
- So you like Mr. White.
- I thought he was a nice guy.

427
00:53:18,611 --> 00:53:21,280
- Jimmy Olsen was fantastic.
MAN: Hey, come here.

428
00:53:21,447 --> 00:53:23,866
Come on, come on. Get in here.
Hurry up. Come on.

429
00:53:24,075 --> 00:53:27,120
- We'd better get out of here.
- I think we'd better do what he says.

430
00:53:27,286 --> 00:53:30,456
MAN: Come on, come on. Get in here.
- Don't do anything.

431
00:53:30,623 --> 00:53:31,999
MAN: That's it.
- We're coming.

432
00:53:32,166 --> 00:53:34,293
- Come on.
- We're coming. Excuse me.

433
00:53:34,460 --> 00:53:35,670
- Go on, back there.
- Here?

434
00:53:35,837 --> 00:53:37,797
Please don't point that at me, sir.

435
00:53:37,964 --> 00:53:40,299
- You could hurt somebody with that.
- Yeah, yeah.

436
00:53:40,466 --> 00:53:43,302
- Okay, okay, hold it there.
- Just a minute, mister.

437
00:53:43,469 --> 00:53:46,472
I realize of course that times
are tough for some these days...

438
00:53:46,639 --> 00:53:48,141
...but this isn't the answer.

439
00:53:48,307 --> 00:53:52,478
You can't solve society's problems
with a gun.

440
00:53:52,645 --> 00:53:56,733
You know something, buddy? You're
right. I'm gonna turn over a new leaf.

441
00:53:56,899 --> 00:54:00,069
Good for you, sir. That's the spirit.
He doesn't really want to hurt anybody.

442
00:54:00,236 --> 00:54:01,320
Uh-huh.

443
00:54:01,487 --> 00:54:04,323
- Right after I rip off this lady's purse.
- Of course.

444
00:54:04,490 --> 00:54:06,492
Now come on, lady, hand it over.

445
00:54:06,659 --> 00:54:09,245
Lois, I think maybe you better...

446
00:54:13,332 --> 00:54:15,835
CLARK:
Lois, what are you doing?

447
00:54:19,005 --> 00:54:20,506
[GRUNTING]

448
00:54:29,849 --> 00:54:32,226
Clark! Clark.

449
00:54:32,393 --> 00:54:35,605
Clark, are you all right? Clark!

450
00:54:35,772 --> 00:54:37,648
What happened?

451
00:54:37,899 --> 00:54:40,026
Golly. I guess I must have fainted.

452
00:54:40,193 --> 00:54:41,861
Fainted?

453
00:54:42,028 --> 00:54:44,655
- You fainted?
- Sorry.

454
00:54:56,292 --> 00:54:57,710
Swell.

455
00:54:57,877 --> 00:55:00,463
Really, Lois, supposing that man
had shot you?

456
00:55:00,671 --> 00:55:04,884
Is it worth risking your life over $10, two
credit cards, a hairbrush, and a lipstick?

457
00:55:05,802 --> 00:55:08,387
- How did you know that?
- Know what?

458
00:55:09,263 --> 00:55:12,475
You just described the exact contents
of my purse.

459
00:55:13,184 --> 00:55:14,560
Hm-

460
00:55:14,936 --> 00:55:17,814
Um, wild guess.

461
00:55:20,900 --> 00:55:22,401
Taxi!

462
00:55:26,739 --> 00:55:29,116
- Hey.
- Hi, Otis.

463
00:55:39,418 --> 00:55:42,630
- So, what's happening, partner?
- Look what we got.

464
00:55:42,797 --> 00:55:45,258
- Let's take him.
- Wait a minute.

465
00:55:45,424 --> 00:55:48,261
Maybe he'll lead us
to the big man himself.

466
00:55:48,427 --> 00:55:51,806
- Lex Luthor?
- You got it, Armus.

467
00:55:52,431 --> 00:55:54,767
We'll make captain by midnight.

468
00:55:56,269 --> 00:55:57,937
Hey, what do you read?

469
00:55:58,104 --> 00:56:00,690
XK-101 rocket to be used.

470
00:56:00,857 --> 00:56:02,441
Hey, what do you read?

471
00:56:02,608 --> 00:56:04,151
- Hey, Matt.
- Hey, hey, Otis.

472
00:56:04,318 --> 00:56:06,529
Just getting the <i>Daily Planet</i> here.

473
00:56:07,488 --> 00:56:08,531
Hey, what do you read?

474
00:56:08,739 --> 00:56:09,782
[BARKING]

475
00:56:09,949 --> 00:56:10,950
Down, down.

476
00:56:11,117 --> 00:56:12,618
Okay, okay.

477
00:56:12,785 --> 00:56:16,455
Okay. All right. See, I'm paying him.
I got a pretzel too.

478
00:56:16,622 --> 00:56:20,167
Thanks, Otis. Okay.
How many did he take, Shutzy?

479
00:56:23,004 --> 00:56:25,882
This is Metropolis 46. We're on foot.
Over and out.

480
00:56:26,048 --> 00:56:27,633
Let's go.

481
00:56:31,888 --> 00:56:34,140
WOMAN [OVER PA]:
<i>Your attention, please.</i>

482
00:56:34,307 --> 00:56:35,975
<i>Your attention, please.</i>

483
00:56:36,142 --> 00:56:39,562
<i>The Metropolis Flyer is now
ready for departure...</i>

484
00:56:39,770 --> 00:56:43,983
<i>...on the upper level, track six,
stopping at New Rochelle.</i>

485
00:56:44,150 --> 00:56:47,320
All right, he's going down to the
train platform. I'm going after him.

486
00:56:47,486 --> 00:56:49,906
Okay, Harry. I'll call for backup.
Be careful, now.

487
00:56:50,072 --> 00:56:52,491
- All right, Armus, all right.
WOMAN: All <i>aboard, please.</i>

488
00:56:54,327 --> 00:56:56,829
<i>Now boarding on the lower level--</i>

489
00:56:56,996 --> 00:56:59,248
MAN: Ten minutes, folks.
Come on, air-conditioned cars.

490
00:56:59,415 --> 00:57:01,834
Mount Vernon, Poughkeepsie,
Glen Corners.

491
00:57:02,001 --> 00:57:04,503
Aboard now. All aboard.
Metropolis Transportation.

492
00:57:04,670 --> 00:57:08,174
Metropolis Transportation.
Buffalo, Syracuse.

493
00:57:08,341 --> 00:57:11,177
Smoking cars are forward.
Move along, now.

494
00:57:11,344 --> 00:57:12,720
Put your luggage up the top.

495
00:57:12,887 --> 00:57:16,557
Smoking cars forward.
All aboard. Boarding.

496
00:57:44,335 --> 00:57:46,963
Armus, Armus, make it track 22.

497
00:57:47,129 --> 00:57:50,967
I seen him, and I'm right on him.
Lower level, track 22.

498
00:57:51,133 --> 00:57:53,094
[TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWS]

499
00:58:02,228 --> 00:58:03,980
[TRAIN BELL DINGING]

500
00:58:27,670 --> 00:58:28,754
So that's it.

501
00:58:44,937 --> 00:58:48,941
LEX: It's amazing that brain can generate
enough power to keep those legs moving.

502
00:59:00,411 --> 00:59:02,038
[TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWS]

503
00:59:08,669 --> 00:59:10,296
[HYDRAULICS HISS]

504
00:59:10,713 --> 00:59:12,965
[GRUNTING]

505
00:59:20,681 --> 00:59:22,016
Ah!

506
00:59:30,858 --> 00:59:32,443
Harry.

507
00:59:34,195 --> 00:59:37,323
Harry, where are you? Harry.

508
00:59:45,081 --> 00:59:46,665
Oh, no.

509
00:59:53,506 --> 00:59:55,007
Harry...

510
00:59:57,176 --> 00:59:58,761
Sick.

511
01:00:06,685 --> 01:00:10,564
- Sick. You're really sick.
- Sick, Miss Teschmacher?

512
01:00:10,731 --> 01:00:14,026
Sick, when I'm mere days from
executing the crime of the century?

513
01:00:14,193 --> 01:00:17,113
No, no, no.
Step away from that, please.

514
01:00:18,405 --> 01:00:22,201
How do you choose to congratulate
the greatest criminal mind of our time?

515
01:00:22,785 --> 01:00:25,037
Do you tell me that I'm brilliant?
Oh, no, no.

516
01:00:25,204 --> 01:00:27,540
That would be too obvious, I grant you.

517
01:00:27,706 --> 01:00:31,377
Charismatic. Fiendishly gifted.

518
01:00:32,044 --> 01:00:33,295
Try "twisted."

519
01:00:39,051 --> 01:00:41,720
Get away from there.
Get away, get away, get away!

520
01:00:43,222 --> 01:00:44,723
Tell me something, Lex.

521
01:00:44,890 --> 01:00:47,768
Why do so many people have to die
for the crime of the century?

522
01:00:47,935 --> 01:00:49,728
Why? You ask why?

523
01:00:49,895 --> 01:00:52,898
Why does the phone always ring
when you're in the bathtub?

524
01:00:54,233 --> 01:00:58,112
Why is the most brilliantly
diabolical leader of our time...

525
01:00:58,279 --> 01:01:00,406
...surrounding himself
with total nincompoops?

526
01:01:00,573 --> 01:01:02,449
I'm back, Mr. Luthor.

527
01:01:02,616 --> 01:01:05,244
Yes, I was just talking about you.

528
01:01:05,744 --> 01:01:07,413
You were followed again.

529
01:01:11,584 --> 01:01:14,420
In spite of those catlike reflexes.

530
01:01:16,922 --> 01:01:20,259
Mr. Luthor. Mr. Luthor, I'm sorry.

531
01:01:20,426 --> 01:01:21,927
Otis.

532
01:01:22,845 --> 01:01:25,055
Is that the newspaper
I asked you to get me?

533
01:01:25,848 --> 01:01:27,099
Yeah.

534
01:01:27,766 --> 01:01:29,768
Why am I not reading it?

535
01:01:31,353 --> 01:01:33,314
Because I haven't given it to you yet?

536
01:01:33,480 --> 01:01:34,940
Right.

537
01:01:39,653 --> 01:01:41,614
At last, it's official.

538
01:01:41,947 --> 01:01:45,284
Thanks to the government,
we will pull off...

539
01:01:45,451 --> 01:01:48,287
...the greatest real-estate swindle
of all time.

540
01:01:48,454 --> 01:01:50,831
Lex, what is this obsession
with real estate?

541
01:01:50,998 --> 01:01:52,958
All the time, "land, land, land."

542
01:01:53,125 --> 01:01:56,128
Miss Teschmacher, when I was
6 years old, my father said to me--

543
01:01:56,295 --> 01:01:57,504
"Get out."

544
01:01:58,797 --> 01:02:02,801
Before that. He said,
"Son, stocks may rise and fall.

545
01:02:02,968 --> 01:02:05,304
Utilities and transportation systems
may collapse.

546
01:02:05,471 --> 01:02:08,349
People are no damn good.
But they will always need land...

547
01:02:08,515 --> 01:02:10,809
...and they'll pay through the nose
to get it."

548
01:02:10,976 --> 01:02:12,811
"Remember," my father said...

549
01:02:12,978 --> 01:02:14,855
- Land.
- Right.

550
01:02:16,482 --> 01:02:20,152
It's a pity that he didn't see
from such humble beginnings...

551
01:02:20,319 --> 01:02:21,987
...how I've created this empire.

552
01:02:22,154 --> 01:02:23,656
An empire? This?

553
01:02:24,490 --> 01:02:26,992
Miss Teschmacher,
how many girls do you know...

554
01:02:27,159 --> 01:02:29,495
...who have a Park Avenue address
like this one?

555
01:02:29,662 --> 01:02:31,413
Park Avenue address?

556
01:02:31,622 --> 01:02:33,332
Two hundred feet below.

557
01:02:33,499 --> 01:02:36,168
Do you realize what people
are shelling out up there...

558
01:02:36,335 --> 01:02:39,338
...for a few miserable rooms
off a common elevator?

559
01:02:39,505 --> 01:02:42,174
TOGETHER:
What more could anyone ask?

560
01:02:47,930 --> 01:02:49,348
- Olsen!
JIMMY: Yeah?

561
01:02:49,515 --> 01:02:52,518
Get this Loch Ness update
right into Composing.

562
01:02:52,851 --> 01:02:56,563
Yeah? No, that's it, Roth.
Put it to bed. Right.

563
01:02:56,730 --> 01:02:59,775
- What are you standing around here for?
- I'm not--

564
01:02:59,942 --> 01:03:02,528
- I wasn't gonna say it.
- Go.

565
01:03:06,573 --> 01:03:09,201
- Ah, the sex maniac profile.
- Right.

566
01:03:09,368 --> 01:03:12,037
Look, 9-5 it's a Pulitzer Prize winner.
What do you bet?

567
01:03:12,204 --> 01:03:13,914
There's no Z in "brassiere."

568
01:03:14,081 --> 01:03:16,375
Hey, nice job
on that union scandal, Kent.

569
01:03:16,542 --> 01:03:18,711
Well, gosh, thanks, Mr. White.

570
01:03:21,380 --> 01:03:22,715
Uh...

571
01:03:22,881 --> 01:03:24,383
Oh, hi, Clark. Good night.

572
01:03:24,550 --> 01:03:27,261
- Here, let me carry that for you.
- Oh, thanks a lot.

573
01:03:27,428 --> 01:03:29,471
Lois, have you got a minute?

574
01:03:29,680 --> 01:03:31,890
Excuse me, please. Lois?

575
01:03:32,057 --> 01:03:35,394
And these two go to the addresses
on the envelope, okay?

576
01:03:35,561 --> 01:03:38,480
Lois, I was wondering if you
would like to have dinner with me?

577
01:03:38,689 --> 01:03:41,275
- Gosh, Clark, I'm sorry. I'm booked.
- Oh.

578
01:03:41,442 --> 01:03:44,320
Air Force One's landing at the airport
and this kid's there...

579
01:03:44,486 --> 01:03:48,157
...to make sure you-know-who answers
a few questions he'd rather duck.

580
01:03:48,324 --> 01:03:50,784
- My goodness, don't you ever let up?
- What for?

581
01:03:50,951 --> 01:03:53,912
I've seen how the other half lives.
My sister, for instance.

582
01:03:54,079 --> 01:03:57,082
Three kids, two cats,
and one mortgage. Yech!

583
01:03:57,249 --> 01:03:58,751
I would go bananas in a week.

584
01:03:58,917 --> 01:04:00,586
Oh, can I take you to the airport?

585
01:04:00,753 --> 01:04:02,963
Not unless you can fly.

586
01:04:03,505 --> 01:04:06,091
- Clark? Ladies.
- Sorry.

587
01:04:06,258 --> 01:04:09,595
- Change my clothes. Thank you. Bye.
- Hey, Lois, maybe we could--?

588
01:04:09,762 --> 01:04:11,430
[SIGHS]

589
01:04:13,015 --> 01:04:14,308
Um...

590
01:04:15,434 --> 01:04:16,810
Lois?

591
01:04:17,102 --> 01:04:21,774
- Would you be a pet and mail that?
- Oh, sure-- Good night.

592
01:04:23,108 --> 01:04:24,610
[EXHALES SHARPLY]

593
01:04:25,778 --> 01:04:29,865
Oh. Going down, please. Going down.

594
01:04:32,493 --> 01:04:35,204
- Going down?
MAN: Going up, up, up.

595
01:04:35,371 --> 01:04:37,122
[CHATTERING]

596
01:04:37,289 --> 01:04:38,791
Good night.

597
01:04:50,469 --> 01:04:52,471
<i>MAN:
Daily Planet Copter One, this is ground.</i>

598
01:04:52,638 --> 01:04:54,139
<i>Planet One, go ahead.</i>

599
01:04:54,306 --> 01:04:58,519
<i>We have Miss Lane here for a ride to
Metropolis Airport to meet Air Force One.</i>

600
01:04:58,685 --> 01:05:00,979
<i>Roger, we're on our way
and have you in sight.</i>

601
01:05:01,146 --> 01:05:03,315
<i>Have one aboard for transfer, over.</i>

602
01:05:03,482 --> 01:05:06,485
<i>Roger, Planet One. You're cleared.
Wind, 0-2-0 at 1-5, gusting.</i>

603
01:05:06,652 --> 01:05:10,489
<i>- Altimeter 2-niner-8-niner.
- Roger, over and out.</i>

604
01:06:02,040 --> 01:06:04,126
[RATTLING]

605
01:06:10,549 --> 01:06:12,426
A malfunction. Can't get liftoff.

606
01:06:12,593 --> 01:06:14,970
MAN: You <i>hooked</i> the <i>tail.</i>
- What's happening?

607
01:06:15,846 --> 01:06:17,222
<i>- Ah!
- Set it down.</i>

608
01:06:17,389 --> 01:06:20,726
Oh, my God! We've lost stabilizer
rotor control, I can't hold it!

609
01:06:20,976 --> 01:06:23,061
[LOIS SCREAMING]

610
01:06:26,064 --> 01:06:28,150
I can't hold it! I can't hold it!

611
01:06:45,667 --> 01:06:47,252
Wake up!

612
01:06:50,631 --> 01:06:52,007
Help!

613
01:06:52,174 --> 01:06:55,093
Help! Help!

614
01:06:56,512 --> 01:06:58,931
[CHATTERING]

615
01:06:59,139 --> 01:07:00,933
[SIRENS APPROACH]

616
01:07:01,141 --> 01:07:02,476
[GRUNTING]

617
01:07:09,775 --> 01:07:11,944
COP:
Come on, step back. Step back, folks.

618
01:07:12,110 --> 01:07:15,280
All right, let's get back a little.
Move over across the street.

619
01:07:18,283 --> 01:07:19,952
Bring the cameras over here. Okay.

620
01:07:20,118 --> 01:07:22,621
Okay, you see the helicopter up there?

621
01:07:29,127 --> 01:07:30,629
Help me!

622
01:07:38,512 --> 01:07:40,806
MAN: All right, move back.
Let the ambulance through.

623
01:07:40,973 --> 01:07:42,808
There's somebody in there!

624
01:07:46,311 --> 01:07:47,813
Help me!

625
01:07:52,859 --> 01:07:54,570
Okay. Come on, hold it. Get back.

626
01:07:58,323 --> 01:08:01,159
Come on. Come on, get off the streets.
Come on, get back.

627
01:08:01,326 --> 01:08:04,162
Move, let the firemen through.

628
01:08:04,329 --> 01:08:06,582
Boys, come on, now. Make a line.

629
01:08:12,087 --> 01:08:14,006
Move to the other side of the street.

630
01:08:15,340 --> 01:08:17,175
Come on. Get along.

631
01:08:17,342 --> 01:08:18,677
Get away from the building.

632
01:08:21,263 --> 01:08:23,473
Hold these crowds back. Move. Move.

633
01:08:25,851 --> 01:08:27,352
Help me!

634
01:08:43,035 --> 01:08:46,038
- Say, Jim, whoa!
- Excuse me.

635
01:08:46,204 --> 01:08:47,998
That's a bad outfit.

636
01:08:48,582 --> 01:08:51,126
- Whoo!
- Okay, Bresslaw, move these people out.

637
01:08:57,257 --> 01:08:59,301
[SCREAMS]

638
01:09:00,552 --> 01:09:02,596
COP:
Oh, God, look up there.

639
01:09:04,056 --> 01:09:05,265
What the hell's that?

640
01:09:06,725 --> 01:09:08,810
- Oh!
- Easy, miss. I've got you.

641
01:09:09,019 --> 01:09:10,729
You-- You've got me?

642
01:09:10,896 --> 01:09:12,898
Who's got you?

643
01:09:13,565 --> 01:09:17,736
I can't believe it. I just
cannot believe it. He got her.

644
01:09:20,822 --> 01:09:22,032
[GASPING]

645
01:09:22,616 --> 01:09:24,576
[SCREAMS]

646
01:09:29,039 --> 01:09:30,290
[CHEERING]

647
01:10:02,447 --> 01:10:04,449
Gentlemen, this man needs help.

648
01:10:06,284 --> 01:10:10,288
Well, I certainly hope this little incident
hasn't put you off flying, miss.

649
01:10:11,206 --> 01:10:15,627
Statistically speaking, of course,
it's still the safest way to travel.

650
01:10:15,961 --> 01:10:18,338
Right. Wait.

651
01:10:23,301 --> 01:10:24,636
Who are you?

652
01:10:25,470 --> 01:10:26,805
A friend.

653
01:10:31,810 --> 01:10:33,645
Bye.

654
01:11:17,898 --> 01:11:20,025
[GRUNTS]

655
01:11:45,467 --> 01:11:48,053
Hi there. Something wrong
with the elevator?

656
01:11:48,261 --> 01:11:49,721
Ah!

657
01:11:55,560 --> 01:11:56,937
Going down.

658
01:12:03,735 --> 01:12:05,403
Nah...

659
01:12:09,074 --> 01:12:10,283
Officer.

660
01:12:13,787 --> 01:12:16,414
Good evening, Officer Mooney.

661
01:12:16,581 --> 01:12:19,417
Well, they say confession
is good for the soul.

662
01:12:20,710 --> 01:12:22,754
I'd listen to this man.

663
01:12:22,921 --> 01:12:24,756
Take him away.

664
01:12:29,344 --> 01:12:30,762
[TIRES SCREECH]

665
01:12:31,096 --> 01:12:33,139
[SIREN WAILS]

666
01:13:09,676 --> 01:13:11,261
Come on. Let's get out of here.

667
01:13:13,638 --> 01:13:15,765
[DISTANT GUNFIRE]

668
01:13:21,521 --> 01:13:23,648
Move your ass. Come on. Come on.

669
01:13:24,316 --> 01:13:26,318
COP:
Okay, let's go. Let's go.

670
01:13:26,484 --> 01:13:30,488
Drop your weapons.
Drop your weapons.

671
01:13:30,655 --> 01:13:32,407
Come on, let's get out of here.

672
01:13:32,574 --> 01:13:34,326
Okay, hold it. Hold it right there.

673
01:13:34,826 --> 01:13:36,494
- Freeze, you turkeys.
MAN 1: Don't shoot.

674
01:13:36,661 --> 01:13:38,288
MAN 2:
Be cool. You got us.

675
01:14:02,896 --> 01:14:04,689
Bad vibrations?

676
01:14:04,856 --> 01:14:08,026
Sergeant, you don't believe me.
I swear, flying.

677
01:14:08,193 --> 01:14:10,445
With a big red cape
and bright red boots, as well.

678
01:14:10,612 --> 01:14:12,781
- Watch the desk.
- Quick as a wink, he was gone.

679
01:14:12,948 --> 01:14:15,867
Flew up in the air again, he did,
like a big blue bird.

680
01:14:16,034 --> 01:14:17,744
- A blue bird...
- You don't believe me.

681
01:14:17,911 --> 01:14:19,704
- ...with bright red boots.
- Flying.

682
01:14:19,871 --> 01:14:21,414
Take off, go back to Murphy's bar.

683
01:14:21,581 --> 01:14:23,708
- Continue what you started.
- Don't believe me.

684
01:14:23,875 --> 01:14:27,545
I'll be off in a few minutes
and I'll meet you there myself.

685
01:14:27,712 --> 01:14:29,381
[CROWD CHEERING]

686
01:14:35,887 --> 01:14:39,391
Mooney, the first bottle's on me.

687
01:14:39,557 --> 01:14:40,976
Let me get my hat.

688
01:14:49,234 --> 01:14:50,902
[THUNDER CRASHING]

689
01:14:51,403 --> 01:14:53,613
GIRL: Hey, Frisky,
will you come down from there.

690
01:14:56,116 --> 01:14:57,909
Hi. I'll get him.

691
01:15:00,954 --> 01:15:02,288
[MEOWS]

692
01:15:02,455 --> 01:15:04,457
Come on. It's all right.

693
01:15:05,583 --> 01:15:07,252
Here you go, miss.

694
01:15:07,419 --> 01:15:10,088
- Gee, thanks, mister.
- Well...

695
01:15:11,089 --> 01:15:13,133
...goodbye, Frisky. So long, now.

696
01:15:16,761 --> 01:15:20,265
- Bye.
- Bye.

697
01:15:21,099 --> 01:15:23,768
Mommy, Mommy,
Frisky was stuck in the tree.

698
01:15:23,935 --> 01:15:26,938
This man swooped out of the sky
and gave him to me.

699
01:15:27,105 --> 01:15:30,150
MOM:
Haven't I told you to stop telling lies?

700
01:15:34,946 --> 01:15:37,198
Metropolis Airport,
this is Air Force One.

701
01:15:37,407 --> 01:15:39,951
- Could we have the weather report?
MAN: Roger, Air Force One.

702
01:15:40,118 --> 01:15:42,328
<i>Metropolis, currently
ceiling 500 overcast.</i>

703
01:15:42,495 --> 01:15:44,456
<i>700 broken,
visibility one half and showers.</i>

704
01:15:44,622 --> 01:15:47,208
<i>Wind 2-4-0 at 2-5,
altimeter niner-niner-eight.</i>

705
01:15:47,417 --> 01:15:48,960
Roger.

706
01:15:49,127 --> 01:15:51,463
Well, it doesn't look too good.
What do you think?

707
01:15:53,465 --> 01:15:55,300
- What the hell was that?
- What happened?

708
01:15:55,467 --> 01:15:58,803
- You lost power in number one.
- Lost power? We lost the whole engine.

709
01:15:59,554 --> 01:16:01,556
- Shut down one.
- Pull one throttle closed.

710
01:16:01,723 --> 01:16:04,309
- Bring up 2 and 3.
- There's not enough pressure...

711
01:16:06,644 --> 01:16:09,981
Mayday, mayday, Metropolis tower.
Air Force One.

712
01:16:10,148 --> 01:16:13,401
We have lost port outboard engine
and part of wing.

713
01:16:13,568 --> 01:16:16,321
Request emergency landing.
What's the position?

714
01:16:16,488 --> 01:16:18,364
Ten miles southwest
of Metropolis Airport.

715
01:16:18,531 --> 01:16:20,992
- Notify them the president's on board.
- Position...

716
01:16:21,159 --> 01:16:23,995
...10 miles southwest
Metropolis Airport.

717
01:16:24,162 --> 01:16:27,957
Heading 3-0-5. Height, 6000 feet.

718
01:16:47,185 --> 01:16:49,854
What the hell happened?
We got our engine back?

